copy \\\"build.gradle.\\\" There's a deterministic setup requested that includes \\\"extra Maven dependencies.\\\" \\n\\nIf we add a new dependency like org.osgi.core 4.2.0, it could replace the old one, but having both might lead to conflicts with duplicate classes. I need to figure out the best way to handle this!\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Evaluating dependencies for testing**\\n\\nI’m considering the current tests, which already have the old dependencies, and adding the new ones that likely fix classes. In Gradle, dependency resolution might not evict the old ones since they’re from different modules, but could that lead to compilation issues? I don’t think so. I should think about including javax.mail:mail:1.4, javax.xml.bind:jaxb-api:2.1, and javax.annotation-api, especially since the POM has these provided. It appears the tests already utilize them, especially relevant for jersey-core.\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_xnGghaU150fEFdBx2hjtB0sb|fc_0140273161488036016a42e167e5fc8193ab9d0a088d8bf7d0", "name": "bash", "arguments": {"command": "python3 - <<'PY'\nimport urllib.request, zipfile, io, subprocess, tempfile, os\n# Download source jar and grep imports/docs maybe\ndata=urllib.request.urlopen('https://repo1.maven.org/maven2/com/sun/jersey/jersey-core/1.14/jersey-core-1.14-sources.jar', timeout=20).read()\nz=zipfile.ZipFile(io.BytesIO(data))\nfor name in z.namelist():\n    if name.endswith('.java'):\n        text=z.read(name).decode(errors='replace')\n        if 'org.osgi.framework.BundleReference' in text or 'javax.mail' in text or 'javax.xml.bind' in text or 'javax.annotation' in text:\n            print('\\n---',name)\n            for line in text.splitlines():\n                if any(x in line for x in ['org.osgi.framework','javax.mail','javax.xml.bind','javax.annotation']):\n                    print(line)\nPY", "timeout": 30}}], "api": "openai-responses", "provider": "OCA", "model": "oca/gpt-5.5", "usage": {"input": 1533, "outpu